      <VBox prefHeight="618.0" prefWidth="744.0" BorderPane.alignment="CENTER">
         <children>
            <Text fill="WHITE" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="In 1969 Ken Thompson and Dennis Ritchie of Bell Laboratories developed the UNIX operating system. It was later rewritten in C to make it more portable and eventually became a widely used operating system.&#10;&#10;A decade or so later, Richard Stallman started working on the GNU (GNU is Not UNIX) project. The GNU General Public License (GPL), a free software license, was also created as a result of GNU as he believes software should be free and open.&#10;&#10;During the time of GNU's creation other efforts such as BSD and MINIX were developed to be UNIX-like systems. However, one thing that all these UNIX-like systems had in common was the lack of a unified kernel.&#10;&#10;Then in 1991,  Linus Torvalds started developing what we now know today as the Linux kernel.&#10;&#10;The kernel is one of the the most important pieces in an operating system, it allows the hardware to talk to the software: The kernel controls pretty much everything that happens on your system." wrappingWidth="711.0">
